; mesh-gradient.form — directed mesh routing: forward toward a destination by hop-distance gradient.
;
; THE ASK (Urs, 2026-06-09):
;   mesh-relay carried a message across a room by FLOODING — every body forwards every new message
;   that still has hops, with no idea where the destination is. Managed flooding reaches everyone, but
;   it touches everyone. The next ring is DIRECTION: if each body knows its own hop-distance to the
;   destination, the message need not flood — it can DESCEND the gradient, stepping body-to-body toward
;   the dest, touching only the path and not the whole room. The distance field IS the map.
;
; THE SHAPE  (runnable: form-stdlib/mesh-gradient.fk · proven: tests/mesh-gradient-band.fk -> 127)
;
;   A neighbor = (list id distance-to-dest). Each body knows its own hop-distance (my-dist) and reads
;   each neighbor's distance. Routing is gradient descent over those distances —
;     1. DOWNHILL ONLY   mg-closer?: a neighbor is a candidate IFF its distance is STRICTLY less than
;                        mine. Sideways (equal distance) and uphill (greater) both fail — the message
;                        only ever moves nearer the destination, never in a circle.
;     2. STEEPEST STEP   mg-next-hop: among the downhill candidates, take the one with the SMALLEST
;                        distance — the deepest single step toward the dest. A min-select carried as a
;                        value, not an index.
;     3. ARRIVED         mg-reached?: my own distance is 0 — I am the destination, no hop is needed.
;   The decision is mg-next-hop — the id of the closest downhill neighbor, or "" when none descends.
;
;   Functions:
;     mg-id / mg-dist  — accessors over a neighbor tuple (id, distance-to-dest).
;     mg-closer?       — the gradient rule: 1 iff this neighbor is STRICTLY closer than me (downhill).
;     mg-reached?      — 1 iff my own distance is 0 (I am the destination; the walk ends here).
;     mg-best-loop     — the inlined min-select: carry the smallest-distance downhill neighbor so far.
;     mg-next-hop      — the id to forward to, or "" when no neighbor descends the gradient.
;
; COMPARISON WITHOUT SUBTRACTION — the load-bearing representation choice:
;   There is no `sub` in the primitive set, but the gradient never needs a difference. "Closer" is a
;   COMPARISON, not a subtraction: mg-closer? is (gt my-dist its-dist) — strictly nearer the dest. The
;   min-select carries the best NEIGHBOR as a value through the recursion (mg-best-loop's `best`), never
;   an index or a running difference. Counting and comparison cover the whole route; the absence of
;   arithmetic shaped the recipe to compare-and-carry, not a workaround bolted onto it.
;
; HOW IT COMPOSES THE SPINE:
;   It EXTENDS mesh-relay.fk over the same body-to-body hop field, swapping blind flooding for directed
;   descent. mesh-relay's law was "forward what is new and has hops" (managed flooding, dest unknown);
;   mesh-gradient's law is "forward to the one neighbor closest to the dest" (gradient descent, dest
;   known by distance). The min-select in mg-best-loop is the same carry-the-best-candidate shape as
;   recognition-router's rr-select-loop — there the best is the strongest reading; here the best is the
;   nearest neighbor; both walk a list keeping one winner and return honest absence when none qualifies.
;   The (if (gt ...) 1 0) settle in mg-closer? and mg-reached? is the same gate discipline mesh-relay's
;   mr-relay? holds: a comparison destined to be tested against 0/1 is settled to an integer first, so
;   the three kernels read it identically (the raw-gate divergence mesh-relay caught live, avoided here).
;
; HONEST LANE:
;   SHIPPED — one node's next-hop choice from a known distance field, proven three-way (-> 127):
;     strict downhill selection, the steepest-step min-select, arrival at distance 0, and honest "" when
;     no neighbor descends (a local minimum, or the node is itself the destination).
;   This is the BODY of one node's forwarding decision for one message. What it does NOT carry yet, and
;   is honestly out of this brick's scope: how the distance field is BUILT and kept fresh (the classic
;   distance-vector exchange — neighbors advertising "my distance is d", each node taking min(neighbor)+1;
;   that is its own recipe), and the actual emit of the message on the chosen neighbor's channel (the
;   channel-port carrier mesh-relay.form already lane-sorts as BUILDABLE). A "" from a non-destination
;   node is a real local minimum — gradient routing stalls there; a fuller router falls back to flooding,
;   which mesh-relay already carries. The two are companions: flood to learn the field, descend to use it.
;
; KIN: mesh-relay.form (the flooding sibling this extends — reach everyone vs. reach the destination) ·
;   reachability.fk (graph reachability — mesh-gradient is reachability WITH a direction, descending a
;   distance field rather than just testing whether an edge path exists) · recognition-router.form (the
;   same min-select shape: carry one best candidate over a list, honest absence when none qualifies) ·
;   device-heartbeat.form (the presence beacon under both — who is in range; the distances ride on it) ·
;   shared-sensing.form (the field of many bodies these messages cross) · lc-honest-lane (the "" is the
;   honesty — a stalled gradient says so rather than guessing a hop).
;
; LINEAGE: mesh-relay proved a message can cross a room hand to hand, blind, by flooding. mesh-gradient
;   is that same field given a sense of direction — each body knowing how far it is from where the
;   message is going, and lending the one step that gets it closest. The mesh is not a new organ; it is
;   the heartbeat field learning to point, so a message walks toward its destination instead of toward
;   everywhere at once.